<a href="https://twitter.com/theatlantic/status/1635416221188341768?s=61&amp;t=2voLMkhJf6P349CqztWSAQ" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/6W_L1nx6Uu78k1yZBKbUq_XTKoF-f-5vMAWBTmIqubs=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvdHdpdHRlcl9uYW1lL3dfOTYvVGhlQXRsYW50aWMuanBn" alt="Twitter avatar for @TheAtlantic" loading="lazy"/>The Atlantic @TheAtlanticThis is a moment of immense peril: Tech companies are rushing ahead to roll out buzzy new AI products, even after the problems with those products have been well documented for years and years, @GaryMarcus writes. </a><a href="http://on.theatln.tc/XPFBJlw" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux." loading="lazy"/>on.theatln.tcWhy Are We Letting the AI Crisis Just Happen?Bad actors could seize on large language models to engineer falsehoods at unprecedented scale.</a><a href="https://twitter.com/theatlantic/status/1635416221188341768?s=61&amp;t=2voLMkhJf6P349CqztWSAQ" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">11:03 PM ∙ Mar 13, 202337Likes14Retweets</a><p>On holiday, but concerned enough to write. A few quick notes:</p><ol><li><p>In <em>The Atlantic </em>earlier<em> </em>today, I wrote <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/03/ai-chatbots-large-language-model-misinformation/673376/?utm_term=2023-03-13T19%3A13%3A08&amp;utm_source=twitter&amp;utm_campaign=the-atlantic&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_content=edit-promo" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">about the  immense near-term risks of mass-produced misinformation</a>: “It will be an uphill, ongoing move-and-countermove arms race from here…  If we don’t start fighting now, democracy may well be overwhelmed by misinformation and consequent polarization—and perhaps quite soon. The 2024 elections could be unlike anything we have seen before.”  </p></li><li><p>On Sam Harris’ podcast Making Sense last week  I <a href="https://www.samharris.org/podcasts/making-sense-episodes/312-the-trouble-with-ai" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">had an intense and fascinating discussion with Berkeley Professsor Stuart Russell</a>, on both short term and long term risks in AI that left me a little shaken. In some way I play the moderate to Stuart Russell’s alarmism. But I’m not <em>that</em> moderate. The disorganized release of Sydney has left me significantly less confident in the AI industry’s competence and eagerness to police itself. Of course I view ChatGPT as only dimly related to artificial general intelligence, but I do see it as dress rehearsal. And, by any reasonable measure, that dress rehearsal went badly. Russell and I discuss. To me the only solution to the long-term risk issue is to build machines with consensus human values, but we are a long way from knowing how to do that, and Russell (who shares my minority view that machines ought to have values they can reason over)) wants machines to learn those values from data, without innate constraint, and I am worried about where insufficiently constrained learning might read. Some said it was the AI podcast of the year; I do think it is worth your time. </p></li><li><p>Katja Grace, lead researcher at <a href="https://aiimpacts.org/about/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">AI Impacts</a> recently surveyed 559 machine learning researchers on how we worried they are about really serious, truly bad outcomes for humanity stemming from AI. A lot of machine learning researchers are worried. And yet most people carry on as if they weren’t.  Psychologist Geoffrey Miller just pointed out the contradiction in no uncertain terms; it’s worth pondering what he had to say:</p><a href="https://twitter.com/garymarcus/status/1635419364974530563?s=12" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/xg3yOfmkkBKwMBUgVwPizMik0_POlv8GzhZynFQC77o=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvdHdpdHRlcl9uYW1lL3dfOTYvR2FyeU1hcmN1cy5qcGc=" alt="Twitter avatar for @GaryMarcus" loading="lazy"/>Gary Marcus @GaryMarcusWhat’s more scary? @KatjaGrace’s study showing how many  ML researchers are forecasting serious levels of AI risk, or the fact that so many ML researchers seem indifferent to that possibility? 

@primalpoly rips into the ML community here: https://t.co/gH3Sc2vvVE <picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Bxa8WE1Rwifer2nTbyyEhthaI3dpwK51K62xIbqT88s=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd182MDAsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZwYnMuc3Vic3RhY2suY29tJTJGbWVkaWElMkZGckl0UGhIV2NBRWY0TXMuanBn"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/c1efjD-lr6kpM0eZEgls2j_bDx87W_cqBdRqBiPiECU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd182MDAsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZwYnMuc3Vic3RhY2suY29tJTJGbWVkaWElMkZGckl0UGhIV2NBRWY0TXMuanBn" alt="Image" loading="lazy"/></picture><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/gRctknNOfG0qOl7wcVlHjz7yH54QA3v_upgjP7Wsozw=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvdHdpdHRlcl9uYW1lL3dfNDAvQUlJbXBhY3RzLmpwZw==" alt="Twitter avatar for @AIImpacts" loading="lazy"/>AI Impacts @AIImpacts2022 survey participants&#39; expected AI outcomes: 14% of area to &#39;extremely bad&#39; (dark grey), 31% total on net bad (dark grey + red) https://t.co/3UEoiEpqUn</a><a href="https://twitter.com/garymarcus/status/1635419364974530563?s=12" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">11:15 PM ∙ Mar 13, 202316Likes2Retweets</a></li></ol><p>Matthew Cobb’s reply to my tweet, below, is worth pondering; not sure we are at that moment, but are we <em>sure</em> we aren’t?</p><a href="https://twitter.com/matthewcobb/status/1635422401768062978?s=12" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/gEhF0cRnSpQl5p87S1sPEaqoln2ECroHQ0yEfhHLkKU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvdHdpdHRlcl9uYW1lL3dfOTYvbWF0dGhld2NvYmIuanBn" alt="Twitter avatar for @matthewcobb" loading="lazy"/>Matthew Cobb @matthewcobb@GaryMarcus @KatjaGrace @primalpoly Only one area of science/technology has been so terrified - and responsible - as to pause work. Genetic engineering has done this four times: 1971, 1974, 2012, 2019. ML - be more like rDNA!</a><a href="https://twitter.com/matthewcobb/status/1635422401768062978?s=12" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">11:27 PM ∙ Mar 13, 2023</a><p>§</p><p>The genie is already partway out of the bottle. Large language models are here to stay, their recipe well understood, and not hard for people skilled in the art to replicate; large pretrained models are out their for the taking on the dark web.  Geoffrey Miller’s lately been campaigning for an outright pause on AI, both research and deployment. I have caused for something less:  stricter regulations governing deployment. Either way I think we need to raise these questions seriously, sooner rather than later.</p><p>Being honest, I can no longer even decide whether I am more concerned about the short-term risks (misinformation undermining democracy tops my own list, though issues of bias continue to loom large) or the long-term risks (e.g, machines with messy values, perhaps induced from mediocre machine learning, and too much power).</p><p>I frankly don’t know what we should do.</p><p>But I am with Ezra Klein in his <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/03/12/opinion/chatbots-artificial-intelligence-future-weirdness.html%20https://www.nytimes.com/2023/03/12/opinion/chatbots-artificial-intelligence-future-weirdness.html" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">most recent op-ed</a>, in which he wrote, “<em>One of two things must happen. Humanity needs to accelerate its adaptation to these technologies or a collective, enforceable decision must be made to slow the development of these technologies. Even doing both may not be enough</em>.”</p><p>We can’t just act as if nothing is happening here. And we can’t act like we have infinite time to decide what to do, either. </p><p><a href="https://garymarcus.substack.com/subscribe?" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Subscribe now</a></p><p><em><strong><a href="http://garymarcus.com" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Gary Marcus</a> </strong>(@garymarcus),<strong> </strong>scientist, bestselling author, and entrepreneur, is a skeptic about current AI but genuinely wants to see the best AI possible for the world—and still holds a tiny bit of optimism. Sign up to his Substack (free!), and <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/01/06/opinion/ezra-klein-podcast-gary-marcus.html" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">listen to him on Ezra Klein</a>. His most recent book, co-authored with Ernest Davis,<a href="http://rebooting.ai/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"> Rebooting AI</a>, is one of Forbes’s 7 Must Read Books in AI. Watch for his new podcast, <a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/humans-vs-machines-with-gary-marcus/id1532110146?i=1000602693237" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Humans versus Machines</a>, this Spring.</em></p><p><a href="https://garymarcus.substack.com/p/caricaturing-noam-chomsky?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&amp;token=eyJ1c2VyX2lkIjoxNDgwNzUyNiwicG9zdF9pZCI6MTA3ODQ2Mzg1LCJpYXQiOjE2Nzg3NTE1OTQsImV4cCI6MTY4MTM0MzU5NCwiaXNzIjoicHViLTg4ODYxNSIsInN1YiI6InBvc3QtcmVhY3Rpb24ifQ.bqgWhDkWwPLwqWtaZZUcZIYSG0jnmPMYUpn5z2zpHsA" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Share</a></p>